    <h1>Energetic Salts of Cubane</h1>
    <div style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: #222;">

        <p><strong>Greetings,</strong></p>

        <p>As you may know, I‘m currently doing quite a bit of work on <strong>cubanes</strong>, and while my primary focus is on pharmaceuticals I couldn’t help but at least do some tests regarding <strong>energetic derivatives</strong>; in the future I‘m planning to make di- and tetranitrocubane too but that’s a different story for now.</p>

        <p>Even seemingly simple, non-energetic derivatives of cubane sometimes actually exhibit energetic properties, with detonation of <strong>dimethyl cubane-1,4-dicarboxylate</strong> having been reported on kugelrohr distillation (<a href="https://apps.dtic.mil/sti/tr/pdf/ADA210368.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">source</a>), and the 1,4-dicarboxylic acid kind of deflagrating on rapid indirect heat, with a more impressive result potentially achievable by confining the solid though I haven’t tried that.</p>

        <p>The fact that the diacid already exhibits some signs of energetic properties raises the question whether this could potentially be improved by preparing the corresponding <strong>carboxylate heavy metal salts</strong>. Further optimization by adding oxygen-containing ligands may be imaginable, though I don’t have any concrete plans in that regard yet.</p>

        <p><strong>It is worth noting that the following two compounds, to my knowledge, have not been reported in literature before.</strong> For the silver salt, there is concern about rearrangement to the corresponding cuneane (<a href="https://pubs.acs.org/doi/10.1021/jacs.3c03207" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">source</a>), but without heating and as a solid salt this process can be expected to be reasonably slow if not completely nonexistent.</p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Preparation Of Cubane-1,4-Dicarboxylic Acid Copper(II) Salt:</h3>

        <p>In a 20 ml glass vial, 96.1 mg of cubane-1,4-dicarboxylic acid (0.5 mmol) were dissolved in exactly 1 ml of 1 molar sodium hydroxide solution, measured with an Eppendorf pipette. The yellowish solution was further diluted with 0.5 ml of water. A random excess of a reasonably concentrated copper(II)-chloride dihydrate solution was added, instantly resulting in a <strong>teal precipitate</strong>, which was collected by gravity filtration and thoroughly washed with distilled water. After drying over silica gel under vacuum, 136.1 mg of a teal amorphous solid were collected, corresponding to a 107.2% yield assuming the anhydrous salt, though as it is likely present as a hydrate of unknown composition, it‘s hard to state a proper yield.</p>

        <p>This material is <strong>insensitive to shock and friction</strong> and on rapid indirect heating only combusts with a bluish-red flame, surprisingly leaving little residue. When confined in aluminum foil (~40 mg tested), a surprisingly strong detonation with a very sooty flame could be perceived, ripping multiple holes into the aluminum foil below, though not resulting in much shrapnel.</p>
    
    </div>

