    <div style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; color: #222;">

    <h3 style="margin-top: 1.5em;">Preparation Of Cubane-1,4-Dicarboxylic Acid Silver(I) Salt:</h3>

    <p><strong>Because of the general tendency of silver salts to be fairly light sensitive, all of the following work was conducted under a source of red light and silver-containing glassware wrapped in aluminum foil when possible.</strong></p>

    <p>In a 20 ml glass vial, 96.1 mg of cubane-1,4-dicarboxylic acid (0.5 mmol) were dissolved in exactly 1 ml of 1 molar sodium hydroxide solution, measured with the help of an Eppendorf pipette, and the yellowish solution further diluted with 0.5 ml of water. A solution of around 250 mg silver nitrate (1.47 mmol) in a minimal amount of water was added, and the resulting <strong>grayish precipitate</strong> collected by vacuum filtration and thoroughly washed with distilled water. After drying over silica gel under vacuum, 176.7 mg of a light grey solid were collected, corresponding to a percent yield of <strong>87.1%</strong>.</p>

    <p>This material can actually be <strong>detonated by strong shock from a hammer</strong>, though I still didn’t notice any friction sensitivity. On indirect heating, the material <strong>deflagrates with a pop</strong>—may even call it at least a partial weak detonation—leaving behind a black residue likely consisting of carbon. On confining in aluminum foil, again ~40 mg were tested, the material <strong>detonates with a sharp bang</strong>, releasing a large amount of soot and ripping a large hole around 5 cm in diameter into the aluminum foil below, fragmenting most of the foil into some very fine shrapnel.</p>

    </div>

